projects.name: FACA Committee Management (FACA)
projects.description: FACAP staff provide management and oversight of CDC FACs, including Special Emphasis Panels (SEPs). FACs and SEPs provide advice and recommendations on a broad range of issues affecting federal policies and programs. Every year the majority of CDC’s overall budget is distributed via contracts, grants, and cooperative agreements to affiliates throughout the world to promote health, prevent disease, injury and disability, and prepare for new health threats.  The committees and panel members are nominated by the applicable programs and SEPs are composed of subject matter experts (SMEs) that are appointed by the Secretary of HHS, CDC Director, World Trade Center Program Administrator, or President of the United States. The CDC Director appoints SEP reviewers. These SEP reviewers are convened in a panel to Team Project created automatically for FACA Committee Management (FACA) review applications and discuss and make initial funding recommendations to the programs. In Fiscal Year 2020, there are 19 FACs engaged with CDC, including the charter that governs the SEPs.

-- Improve Order Lifecycle Management
-- Reduce financial risks
-- Create better accountability
-- Provision for system enhancements

- Business Value – 
-- Replace MACCS and MACCS-1350
-- Better enable the Purchase Card management of audits
-- Enhance user experience
-- Accurate Purchase card order processing and records management.

projects.name: FACA Committee Management (FACA)
projects.description: FACAP staff provide management and oversight of CDC FACs, including Special Emphasis Panels (SEPs). FACs and SEPs provide advice and recommendations on a broad range of issues affecting federal policies and programs. Every year the majority of CDC’s overall budget is distributed via contracts, grants, and cooperative agreements to affiliates throughout the world to promote health, prevent disease, injury and disability, and prepare for new health threats.  The committees and panel members are nominated by the applicable programs and SEPs are composed of subject matter experts (SMEs) that are appointed by the Secretary of HHS, CDC Director, World Trade Center Program Administrator, or President of the United States. The CDC Director appoints SEP reviewers. These SEP reviewers are convened in a panel to Team Project created automatically for FACA Committee Management (FACA) review applications and discuss and make initial funding recommendations to the programs. In Fiscal Year 2020, there are 19 FACs engaged with CDC, including the charter that governs the SEPs.

projects.name: FACA Committee Management (FACA)
projects.description: FACAP staff provide management and oversight of CDC FACs, including Special Emphasis Panels (SEPs). FACs and SEPs provide advice and recommendations on a broad range of issues affecting federal policies and programs. Every year the majority of CDC’s overall budget is distributed via contracts, grants, and cooperative agreements to affiliates throughout the world to promote health, prevent disease, injury and disability, and prepare for new health threats.  The committees and panel members are nominated by the applicable programs and SEPs are composed of subject matter experts (SMEs) that are appointed by the Secretary of HHS, CDC Director, World Trade Center Program Administrator, or President of the United States. The CDC Director appoints SEP reviewers. These SEP reviewers are convened in a panel to Team Project created automatically for FACA Committee Management (FACA) review applications and discuss and make initial funding recommendations to the programs. In Fiscal Year 2020, there are 19 FACs engaged with CDC, including the charter that governs the SEPs.

projects.name: Credit Card Purchasing System (CCPS)
projects.description:
New system Credit Card Purchasing System (CCPS) is been developed by OFR and OCIO.
CCPS will replace MACCS and MACCS-1350 to better manage Purchase Card audits as well as enhance the user experience, resulting in more effective and accurate, purchase card order processing and records management.

Business Need & Business Value Summary: 
- Business need - 
-- Improve Order Lifecycle Management
-- Reduce financial risks
-- Create better accountability
-- Provision for system enhancements

- Business Value – 
-- Replace MACCS and MACCS-1350
-- Better enable the Purchase Card management of audits
-- Enhance user experience
-- Accurate Purchase card order processing and records management.

projects.description: FACAP staff provide management and oversight of CDC FACs, including Special Emphasis Panels (SEPs). FACs and SEPs provide advice and recommendations on a broad range of issues affecting federal policies and programs. Every year the majority of CDC’s overall budget is distributed via contracts, grants, and cooperative agreements to affiliates throughout the world to promote health, prevent disease, injury and disability, and prepare for new health threats.  The committees and panel members are nominated by the applicable programs and SEPs are composed of subject matter experts (SMEs) that are appointed by the Secretary of HHS, CDC Director, World Trade Center Program Administrator, or President of the United States. The CDC Director appoints SEP reviewers. These SEP reviewers are convened in a panel to Team Project created automatically for FACA Committee Management (FACA) review applications and discuss and make initial funding recommendations to the programs. In Fiscal Year 2020, there are 19 FACs engaged with CDC, including the charter that governs the SEPs.

projects.name: NGSQI
projects.description:
A development environment for the Next Generation Sequencing Quality Initiative Team.

The Next Generation Sequencing (NGS) Quality Initiative offers a foundational, NGS-focused quality management system (QMS) based on the Clinical & Laboratory Standards Institute (CLSI) framework of 12 Quality Systems Essentials (QSEs). Laboratory professionals, including quality managers, microbiologists, bioinformaticians, and others involved with development and implementation of NGS-based tests can find more than 100 ready-to-implement guidance documents, customizable standard operating procedures, and other tools to download and use for free. These tools are designed to be customized by laboratories to meet their specific needs. Find tools to address the many challenges public health and clinical laboratories face in pursuing high-quality results using NGS, whether you are establishing a new QMS or enhancing an existing one.

The NGS Quality Initiative is funded by CDC’s Office of Advanced Molecular Detection, and is co-led by the Division of Laboratory Systems and the Association of Public Health Laboratories.

projects.name: ARXDM
projects.description:
The AR Lab Network supports national testing for antimicrobial resistant bacterial and fungal pathogens across 56 jurisdictions and through 7 regional laboratories. The AR Lab Network conducts diverse antimicrobial resistance testing for many pathogens. Data is reported to CDC ARLN SME groups (DHQP, GC, MDB) through DAART (Data for Action on Antimicrobial Threats) - a system hosted by APHL AIMS. Currently, CDC SME groups experience numerous challenges associated with the use of DAART data, limiting their ability to make near real-time public health decisions. CDC SMEs spend an inordinate amount of time on data wrangling and data cleaning - all using a different stack of tools and technologies - limiting their ability to conduct analysis and generate insights to make these public health decisions. This investment is focused on establishing a transactional data model and moving DAART functionality to CDC while keeping APHL AIMS as a trusted intermediary to ensure connection to PHLs.

The new dataflow will be STLT to APHL (route-no-read) to 1CDP (Redaction, Validation, Transformation) to the EDAV Transactional Database to Programs (DHQP/GC/MDB).

projects.description:
I have a team member who needs Team Foundation Server (TFS) installed on his CDC desktop in order to store source code for the IIS Dashboard, which is a software tool used by IISSB/IIS/NCRID.  I understand that there is no cost to the C/I/O for this software but that a request must be submitted via email with the information below:
  *   Name for your TFS Project.  Example: http://tfs.cdc.gov/tfs/[your<http://tfs.cdc.gov/tfs/%5byour> project name]  IISDashboard
     *   (IIS stands for Immunization Support Services)
  *   CDC User ID/Contact information for primary and secondary TFS Administrators – primary Dave Farkas (IYW3), Secondary Ramesh Thalluru (RKT5)
  *   CDC User ID/Contact information for a Business Steward who must be an FTE  - Kafayat Adeniyi (KGA9)
  *   CDC User ID/Contact information for a Security Steward. Do not list your ISSO and/or TSE in this role  - Kafayat Adeniyi (KGA9)
  *   Specify a Process Template for your single TFS project: Agile, Scrum, or CMMI<https://www.visualstudio.com/en-us/docs/work/guidance/choose-process>.  – Agile
  *   Specify a versioning technique: TFS or GIT?<https://www.visualstudio.com/en-us/docs/tfvc/comparison-git-tfvc> – TFS
  *   Are you planning to use Build and Scanning services? If Yes, see Request Build Services<https://esp.cdc.gov/sites/tfs/Team%20Foundation%20Server%20Tips/Build,%20Release,%20and%20Scanning%20Agents.aspx> (you may implement build services at a later date) - No
Write a short justification for this TFS project:
Our team previously used Apache Subversion (SVN) to maintain current and historical versions of development files such as source code, web pages, and documentation.  However, our developer’s desktop was recently reimaged by ITSO and he is not able to reinstall this open source code.  Instead, we think it best to use Team Foundation Server (TFS) since it is the standard tool used at CDC for maintaining versions of source code, etc.  Since there is no cost to our C/I/O, we are requesting to use this software instead.

projects.name: NGSQI
projects.description:
A development environment for the Next Generation Sequencing Quality Initiative Team.

The Next Generation Sequencing (NGS) Quality Initiative offers a foundational, NGS-focused quality management system (QMS) based on the Clinical & Laboratory Standards Institute (CLSI) framework of 12 Quality Systems Essentials (QSEs). Laboratory professionals, including quality managers, microbiologists, bioinformaticians, and others involved with development and implementation of NGS-based tests can find more than 100 ready-to-implement guidance documents, customizable standard operating procedures, and other tools to download and use for free. These tools are designed to be customized by laboratories to meet their specific needs. Find tools to address the many challenges public health and clinical laboratories face in pursuing high-quality results using NGS, whether you are establishing a new QMS or enhancing an existing one.

The NGS Quality Initiative is funded by CDC’s Office of Advanced Molecular Detection, and is co-led by the Division of Laboratory Systems and the Association of Public Health Laboratories.

projects.name: NGSQI
projects.description:
A development environment for the Next Generation Sequencing Quality Initiative Team.

The Next Generation Sequencing (NGS) Quality Initiative offers a foundational, NGS-focused quality management system (QMS) based on the Clinical & Laboratory Standards Institute (CLSI) framework of 12 Quality Systems Essentials (QSEs). Laboratory professionals, including quality managers, microbiologists, bioinformaticians, and others involved with development and implementation of NGS-based tests can find more than 100 ready-to-implement guidance documents, customizable standard operating procedures, and other tools to download and use for free. These tools are designed to be customized by laboratories to meet their specific needs. Find tools to address the many challenges public health and clinical laboratories face in pursuing high-quality results using NGS, whether you are establishing a new QMS or enhancing an existing one.

The NGS Quality Initiative is funded by CDC’s Office of Advanced Molecular Detection, and is co-led by the Division of Laboratory Systems and the Association of Public Health Laboratories.

projects.name: PHIAT IT Support
projects.description:
This project tracks all system and tools development for NCEH/ATSDR/OD/OS/PHIAT.

Potential cloning issue with GitHub - unable to clone due to an SSL certificate error. How to fix:

1. Download the HTTPS certificate from the browser.
2. Save it in your UserID folder.
3. Right-click on the cert and select Install Certificate
4. Go to Visual Studio >  Tools > Command Line > Developer Powershell
5. run this command in the powershell: git config --global http.sslCAInfo "C:\Users\{your userId}\devops2.cdc.gov.crt"
6. Go to Visual Studio and clone the repo
7. In my case, I left the path as is
8. Cloning was successful after this

When Sequoia runs, you may run into an SSL cert issue, as Sequoia runs on HTTPS. So try these commands toclear your local certs and re-install them
dotnet dev-certs https --clean 
dotnet dev-certs https --trust 
dotnet dev-certs https –check

projects.name: COVID-19
projects.description: Surveillance architecture to receive, display, and send COVID-19 EHR information from Public and Private Health Labs.  The product name is COVID-19 Electronic Lab Reporting System (CELRS).  Data Lake for Ingesting Lab Reports and Admission Discharge Notices (ADT) of different types (HL7 2.x ELR , HL72.x LRI,HL7 2.x ADT FHIR R3/R4 , eCR/CCDA, CSV/XLSX/Flat File)  Processing pipelines that supports receiving data streams from to address multiple ways the data streams are coming in for COVID19 testing. These pipelines then validate structure and vocabularies, transform, translate vocabularies for each of the streams to merge the data into a COVID19 Data Lake. The Data Processing is event driven and make streaming of cleaned merged data across to analytical tools in real time.

projects.name: DNPAO_RAPID
projects.description:
Rapid Analysis of Policy and Program Documents (RAPID) is a web-based tool that optimizes policy surveillance and evaluation by employing advanced artificial intelligence (AI) to automate the analysis of extensive document collections, including state and local policies. RAPID improves the efficiency of document-based research tasks, such as policy surveillance, by leveraging AI. RAPID can be utilized to semantically search through large amounts of documents for relevant material. Users can then ask AI various open-ended questions about chosen subsets of available documents, saving the provided answers and exporting them to further inform their research.
MITRE has developed an Artificial Intelligence powered prototype application, originally referred to as Research Automation Methods for Policy and Program (RAMP), and now named Rapid Analysis of Policy and Program Information from Documentation (RAPID) for the DNPAO division of the CDC NCCDPHP. 
The tool, originally built for DNPAO, has broader appeal and use cases and therefore the DNPAO and OIIRM has asked for this application to be migrated from MITRE’s development sandbox environment to the OCIO NCCDPHP Development environment where Peraton will transition and promote the system to the production environment.
